Apr 19 2009 	everything I needed/wanted in a hotel	I've read several reviews on various resorts/hotels/destinations, and this is my first review. I realize these reviews are as much about the reviewer as they are about the destination, so a bit about me (I'll try not to sound like a personal ad): I'm Canadian (born and raised and live in Toronto downtown)I'm a 30 y/o male who is really active in working out, sports, etc. I have travelled quite a bit and stayed at luxury as well as not-so-luxury hotels.Having said that, I have read reviews in the past where people complain about a crack they found in a tile or a stain on the carpet of the hotel. My advice to these people: you are spending too much time in your hotel, get outside.I chose this hotel based on the price, as this was my first time in San Francisco and I did hear that its location is close to the Tenderloin district, but I'll give you some tips later on for dealing with that. STAFFCourteous and check in/out was quick. They greeted me every morning and &quot;Francisco&quot; checked me in and pointed out all the ammenities in the hotel. Every time I had a question, the person at the front desk was very helpful. I have stayed at hotels before and spent five times as much $ on my stay and not received the same warm and personal service as the staff at the Opal. Great job. ROOMMy room had a bed and I was happy. Ok, for those who want to hear about all the &quot;extras&quot;, my room also had a t.v, a dresser, a desk, a huge walk in closet, a clean bathroom with a shower stall (no tub). The views were of the street from the bedroom and in the bathroom the view was a brick wall ( which I enjoyed for privacy and also allowed for fresh air). I also had a coffee maker which I used twice. If you're looking for mints left on your pillow and turn down service- stay at the Ritz. INTERNETAwesome. Just plugged in my laptop and was up and running in 2 minutes. This is completely free and was very much appreciated - thank you.BREAKFASTAmazing. Something small, but I noticed: the person stocking the breakfast condiments was extremely effecient. In fact, the cream cheese basket seemed to always have 50 or so little cream cheese packages. Every time I took a few, she would replenish them. Good job. As for the breakfast itself - perfect start to the day. Coffee/Juice/Tea, Cereals, fresh bagels (very good), you can toast your bread/bagels and there are about 8 or so toasters so I didnt have to wait. Just one complaint (but I always complain about this) is that the cups for the juice and coffee were too tiny for me. I drink too much, I know. Actually I ended up bringing my own starbucks cups (venti) to fill up on juice and coffee much the the discerning looks of some of the foreign guests. Its either that or get up every 2 minutes to re-fill , so don't judge me. Some ADVICE: Get there early - it opens at 6:30, if you're like me and like to be in and out quickly. I found people just hanging around talking in front of the toaster and not using them, which I found a bit annoying, so I gave them a discerning look and they seemed to get it. :)LOCATIONSo, the majority of the negative reviews talk about the location. Here is the double edged sword. The hotel is close to everything - very good location in that respect. Not right downtown so to speak, but quite close to it. However, it boarders on Tenderloin - which is our equivalent to Gerrard/Jarvis area in Toronto. A lot of you have complained about the homeless people and sketchy characters and I thought to myself before I arrived &quot;whatever, I live in Toronto, I can handle it&quot;. Here is the thing (bear in mind I loved San Francisco) but San Francisco has a homeless problem. Sorry, but true. The only other comparable city to this would be Paris where homeless kids and breastfeeding mothers line on some of the most exclusive Paris streets. Ok, now that thats over with, know that I totally had an amazing time in San Francisco, but I wanted to call this out to say that it is not this hotel's fault that the city has more homeless people in it, therefore an area like Tenderloin will just have &quot;more&quot; homeless people. I did walk up and down Geary street (street next to Opal) without incident other than being asked for change, however I dont think I'd do it at night with shopping bags, etc. I have a tip though, and you'll thank me for it. Walk east just a bit - past Geary, and you'll be in Nob Hill area - expensive homes, nice area. You will soon be at one of the following streets: Sutter will lead you right to Union Square walk down there for 10 minutes and you'll be in the best shopping district. Bush street and California will lead you right to Financial District and China Town, again in 10 minutes. Or you can walk down Bush and once you get down far enough, you can come back toward Geary and end up at Union Square (if you're concerned about avoiding Tenderloin, this is your best route).Take a cable car on California Street to downtown (after you get a Starbucks around Van Ness and California) - trust me on this one...the cable car will not have any tourists - only local San Fran's and you. You will have a view of the whole city for a 10 minute ride which you 'll never forget. MEL's DINERI can't not mention this great little Diner next door (yes its also attached, but get outside and enter through the main entrance). It stays open late and is open early and I dont usually eat any fast food or greasy stuff, but I could not resist and every meal I got here was superb and well prepared. Staff was great too. Hope you found this review helpful. Not all travellers are alike, so if you're like me you'll have a great time here.San Francisco is an amazing city and I met a lot of people (locals, not other tourists). I'm the type who doesnt like to necessarily socialize with my fellow hotel patrons (the less time I spend in a hotel, the better), so I prefer getting in with the people who actually live in the city, which makes all the difference for me. However, for the time I did spend in the hotel it was great - everything I wanted for an enjoyable trip. I'd reccommend this hotel, yes. You won't have luxury, but for the money, this hotel is well worth it.	
